<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>It was also Huddleston who helped Bra Hugh to study music overseas after he went into exile in 1961.He lived in various countries before returning home in 1991.Bra Hugh had an appeal across all generations and was not afraid to voice his opinions.Not many people could voice their disapproval of women wearing wigs in this day and age and get away with it.But he did, refusing to take selfies with women in wigs.He also voiced disapproval of Africans who ditched their languages for English.Caiphus Semenya paid his respects at Bra Hugh’s home.
Photo: Lucky Morajane“A decade or two from now, African society will be the first in history to have abandoned its native tongues in preference for those manipulated by colonial rule if we do not soon re-institute our own languages in our homes, schools and in social interaction with each other.”But mostly, Bra Hugh will be remembered for his music and his live performances, where he had young and old eating from the palm of his hand.We will all remember his special dances and footwork on stage.A lot has been written about his contribution to the struggle against apartheid.He joked that musicians who were part of the struggle will go down in history as an army that spent their time singing, rather than fighting.He is said to have recorded over 38 chart-topping albums and to have sold over five million copies worldwide.Mbongeni Ngema paid his respects at Bra Hugh’s home.
Photo: Lucky MorajaneHis single Grazing in the Grass sold over four million units worldwide.Bra Hugh also had many collaborations, appearing as a guest artist on over 1 000 albums.